@almarklein sorry for the delay, I finally found the time to give this a good look. For the most part I only see minor style improvements, but there are some areas in the Cython with low-hanging-fruit optimizations possible - especially refactoring variables out of innermost loops and aggressive precalculating / referencing in the main `marching_cubes` Cython function. 

There are also some places where typed memoryviews could be used to good effect. Those gains are real, but secondary to refactoring and precalc/referencing. If memoryviews aren't your favorite thing, don't worry about them for now.

There does appear to be [a subtle typo in this line](https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/pull/2052#discussion-diff-71091044R79) pertaining to the classic code path, which may explain the difference between the classic implementations.

@stefanv For me there are three reasons in favor of a new ``ridge``module: First, there are four ridge filters now, which is not so much fewer than the five edge filters (sobel, scharr, prewitt, roberts, laplace; although they typically come with different v/h flavors).
Second, I'm thinking about extending the set of ridge filters by the one(s) introduced in [6]. While strictly speaking these filters just replace the Hessian matrix with a phase congruency tensor (i.e., leaving the  

[6] Obara, B., Fricker, M., Gavaghan, D., & Grau, V. (2012). Contrast-independent curvilinear structure detection in biomedical images. IEEE Transactions on Image Processing, 21(5), 2572-2581.

